expose aiAssistant

doc [md, html] aiAssistant() {
  # AI Assistant Integration

  TLang ships a Model Context Protocol server that gives AI coding assistants
  — Claude, Cursor, GitHub Copilot, and others — full access to TLang's compiler,
  runtime, and embedded documentation. The MCP server turns any MCP-compatible
  assistant into a TLang-aware pair programmer.

  [section "start"
    ## Starting the MCP Server

    [code "bash"
      tlang mcp-server
    ]

    The server communicates over stdin/stdout using JSON-RPC 2.0, following the
    MCP 2024-11-05 specification. Connect it to your AI assistant using the
    assistant's MCP configuration.

    Example configuration for Claude Desktop (claude_desktop_config.json):

    [code "json"
      {
        "mcpServers": {
          "tlang": {
            "command": "tlang",
            "args": ["mcp-server"]
          }
        }
      }
    ]
  ]

  [section "tools"
    ## Available Tools

    The MCP server exposes a set of tools that mirror the TLang CLI.
    The assistant can call these tools directly during a conversation:

    [list "unordered"
      - tlang_init — initialise a new TLang project with a manifest.yml
      - tlang_compile — compile a .tlang file to bytecode without running it
      - tlang_run — run a pre-compiled .tlang bytecode file
      - tlang_both — compile and run in a single step (the typical workflow)
      - tlang_package — package a project into a .tbag archive for publishing
      - tlang_clean — remove compiled bytecode caches
      - tlang_index — index the current project for symbol search
      - tlang_topic — retrieve embedded documentation on a specific TLang topic
    ]

    When a project context is active, the server also exposes dynamic tools
    derived from the project's exposed functions, allowing the assistant to
    call specific generators directly.
  ]

  [section "resources"
    ## Resources

    The MCP server exposes embedded documentation as resources the assistant
    can read to understand TLang before generating code:

    [list "unordered"
      - tlang://guide — the full TLang onboarding guide
      - tlang://project — project structure and manifest reference
      - tlang://lang — language syntax reference
      - tlang://templates — template block reference (lang, doc, style, data, cmd, raw)
      - tlang://helpers — helper function patterns
      - tlang://builtins — standard library module reference
      - tlang://patterns — idiomatic TLang patterns
      - tlang://mistakes — common mistakes and how to avoid them
    ]

    These resources are served directly from the binary — no internet connection required.
  ]

  [section "prompts"
    ## System Prompt

    The MCP server provides a ready-made system prompt for AI assistants.
    When connected, the assistant automatically receives context about:

    [list "unordered"
      - TLang syntax and semantics
      - Template types and their calling conventions
      - The set + template binding pattern
      - The standard library API
      - Common pitfalls (StringBuilder.build vs toString, etc.)
      - How to write idiomatic TLang code
    ]

    This eliminates the need to paste TLang documentation into every conversation.
    The assistant starts with full context.
  ]

  [section "workflow"
    ## AI-Native Workflow

    The intended workflow with TLang and an AI assistant:

    [list "ordered"
      - Describe your model to the assistant (entities, fields, relationships)
      - The assistant writes the TLang templates using set declarations and template blocks
      - The assistant calls tlang_both to compile and run the templates
      - TLang generates all target files — the assistant reviews the output
      - You add more entities or refine the templates — the assistant regenerates
    ]

    The AI does the creative work (understanding your domain and writing the template)
    once. TLang handles the mechanical work (generating the same pattern across all
    entities) at zero additional AI cost.

    A project with 200 entities costs the same in AI tokens as a project with 2 —
    because the AI writes one template, not 200 files.
  ]

  [section "project-context"
    ## Project Context

    Use the set_project_context tool to point the MCP server at a TLang project:

    [code "bash"
      # In the assistant conversation:
      # "Set the project context to my-app/"
    ]

    Once set, the server indexes the project and exposes its exposed functions
    as dynamic tools. The assistant can then call your project's generators
    directly without writing any CLI commands.
  ]
}
